KW  - Monthly stock and corporate bond returns
KW  - Past 1-month stock winners and losers
KW  - 52-week stock price anchors
KW  - Market sentiment
AB  - We show that the expensiveness of a stock’s price, relative to its 52-week price history (or price-to-52-week-anchor, PTA), predicts a striking cross-sectional variation in both the monthly stock returns of past-winner stocks and the monthly corporate bond returns of past-loser stocks. The stock returns for past-winner stocks with a high PTA strongly outperform past-winner stocks with a low PTA. And, the corporate-bond returns of firms with high-PTA, past-loser stocks strongly outperform those with low-PTA, past-loser stocks. We show how these PTA-based empirical patterns vary both in the time-series and in the cross-section in multiple dimensions, with results that suggest the PTA patterns are stronger during better sentiment times and for securities that likely have higher valuation uncertainty. Our new 52-week price-anchor metric equally uses information in both a stock’s price-to-52-week-high ratio and its price-to-52-week-low ratio. Our findings suggest that a stock’s 52-week PTA can induce a bias that influences how investors assess recent valuation news, impacting both subsequent one-month stock and corporate bond returns.
